# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hartree-fock
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] The basis set can either be composed of atomic orbitals (yielding the linear combination of atomic orbitals approach), which is the usual choice within the quantum chemistry community; plane waves which are typically used within the solid state community, or real-space approaches.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Several types of atomic orbitals can be used: Gaussian-type orbitals, Slater-type orbitals, or numerical atomic orbitals.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Out of the three, Gaussian-type orbitals are by far the most often used, as they allow efficient implementations of post-Hartree–Fock methods.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] In modern computational chemistry, quantum chemical calculations are performed using a finite set of basis functions.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] When the finite basis is expanded towards an (infinite) complete set of functions, calculations using such a basis set are said to approach the complete basis set (CBS) limit.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] In this context, *basis function* and *atomic orbital* are sometimes used interchangeably, although the basis functions are usually not true atomic orbitals.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Within the basis set, the wavefunction is represented as a vector, the components of which correspond to coefficients of the basis functions in the linear expansion.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] In such a basis, one-electron operators correspond to matrices (a.k.a. rank two tensors), whereas two-electron operators are rank four tensors.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] When molecular calculations are performed, it is common to use a basis composed of atomic orbitals, centered at each nucleus within the molecule (linear combination of atomic orbitals ansatz).
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] The physically best motivated basis set are Slater-type orbitals (STOs), which are solutions to the Schrödinger equation of hydrogen-like atoms, and decay exponentially far away from the nucleus.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] It can be shown that the molecular orbitals of Hartree–Fock and density-functional theory also exhibit exponential decay.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Furthermore, S-type STOs also satisfy Kato's cusp condition at the nucleus, meaning that they are able to accurately describe electron density near the nucleus.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] However, hydrogen-like atoms lack many-electron interactions, thus the orbitals do not accurately describe electron state correlations.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Unfortunately, calculating integrals with STOs is computationally difficult and it was later realized by Frank Boys that STOs could be approximated as linear combinations of Gaussian-type orbitals (GTOs) instead.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Because the product of two GTOs can be written as a linear combination of GTOs, integrals with Gaussian basis functions can be written in closed form, which leads to huge computational savings (see John Pople).
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Dozens of Gaussian-type orbital basis sets have been published in the literature.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Basis sets typically come in hierarchies of increasing size, giving a controlled way to obtain more accurate solutions, however at a higher cost.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] The smallest basis sets are called *minimal basis sets*.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] A minimal basis set is one in which, on each atom in the molecule, a single basis function is used for each orbital in a Hartree–Fock calculation on the free atom.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] For atoms such as lithium, basis functions of p type are also added to the basis functions that correspond to the 1s and 2s orbitals of the free atom, because lithium also has a 1s2p bound state.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] For example, each atom in the second period of the periodic system (Li – Ne) would have a basis set of five functions (two s functions and three p functions).
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] A minimal basis set may already be exact for the gas-phase atom at the self-consistent field level of theory.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] In the next level, additional functions are added to describe polarization of the electron density of the atom in molecules.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] These are called **polarization functions**.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] For example, while the minimal basis set for hydrogen is one function approximating the 1s atomic orbital, a simple polarized basis set typically has two s- and one p-function (which consists of three basis functions: px, py and pz).
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] This adds flexibility to the basis set, effectively allowing molecular orbitals involving the hydrogen atom to be more asymmetric about the hydrogen nucleus.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] This is very important for modeling chemical bonding, because the bonds are often polarized.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Similarly, d-type functions can be added to a basis set with valence p orbitals, and f-functions to a basis set with d-type orbitals, and so on.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Another common addition to basis sets is the addition of **diffuse functions**.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] These are extended Gaussian basis functions with a small exponent, which give flexibility to the "tail" portion of the atomic orbitals, far away from the nucleus.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Diffuse basis functions are important for describing anions or dipole moments, but they can also be important for accurate modeling of intra- and inter-molecular bonding.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] The most common minimal basis set is STO-nG, where n is an integer.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] The STO-nG basis sets are derived from a minimal Slater-type orbital basis set, with *n* representing the number of Gaussian primitive functions used to represent each Slater-type orbital.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Minimal basis sets typically give rough results that are insufficient for research-quality publication, but are much cheaper than their larger counterparts.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] There are several other minimum basis sets that have been used such as the MidiX basis sets.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] During most molecular bonding, it is the valence electrons which principally take part in the bonding.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] In recognition of this fact, it is common to represent valence orbitals by more than one basis function (each of which can in turn be composed of a fixed linear combination of primitive Gaussian functions).
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Basis sets in which there are multiple basis functions corresponding to each valence atomic orbital are called valence double, triple, quadruple-zeta, and so on, basis sets (zeta, ζ, was commonly used to represent the exponent of an STO basis function).
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Since the different orbitals of the split have different spatial extents, the combination allows the electron density to adjust its spatial extent appropriate to the particular molecular environment.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] In contrast, minimal basis sets lack the flexibility to adjust to different molecular environments.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] The notation for the *split-valence* basis sets arising from the group of John Pople is typically *X-YZg*.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] In this case, *X* represents the number of primitive Gaussians comprising each core atomic orbital basis function.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] The *Y* and *Z* indicate that the valence orbitals are composed of two basis functions each, the first one composed of a linear combination of *Y* primitive Gaussian functions, the other composed of a linear combination of *Z* primitive Gaussian functions.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] In this case, the presence of two numbers after the hyphens implies that this basis set is a *split-valence double-zeta* basis set.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Split-valence triple- and quadruple-zeta basis sets are also used, denoted as *X-YZWg*, *X-YZWVg*, etc.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Polarization functions are denoted by two different notations.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] The original Pople notation added "*" to indicate that all "heavy" atoms (everything but H and He) have a small set of polarization functions added to the basis (in the case of carbon, a set of 3d orbital functions).
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] The "**" notation indicates that all "light" atoms also receive polarization functions (this adds a set of 2p orbitals to the basis for each hydrogen atom).
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Eventually it became desirable to add more polarization to the basis sets, and a new notation was developed in which the number and types of polarization functions are given explicitly in parentheses in the order (heavy,light) but with the principal quantum numbers of the orbitals implicit.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] For example, the * notation becomes (d) and the ** notation is now given as (d,p).
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] If instead 3d and 4f functions were added to each heavy atom and 2p, 3p, 3d functions were added to each light atom, the notation would become (df,2pd).
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] In all cases, diffuse functions are indicated by either adding a + before the letter G (diffuse functions on heavy atoms only) or ++ (diffuse functions are added to all atoms).
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] The Pople basis sets were originally developed for use in Hartree-Fock calculations.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Since then, correlation-consistent or polarization-consistent basis sets (see below) have been developed which are usually more appropriate for correlated wave function calculations.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Some of the most widely used basis sets are those developed by Dunning and coworkers, since they are designed for converging post-Hartree–Fock calculations systematically to the complete basis set limit using empirical extrapolation techniques.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] For first- and second-row atoms, the basis sets are cc-pVNZ where *N* = *D*,*T*,*Q*,5,6,...
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] The 'cc-p', stands for 'correlation-consistent polarized' and the 'V' indicates that only basis sets for the valence orbitals are of multiple-zeta quality.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] (Like the Pople basis sets, the core orbitals are of single-zeta quality.) They include successively larger shells of polarization (correlating) functions (*d*, *f*, *g*, etc.).
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] More recently these 'correlation-consistent polarized' basis sets have become widely used and are the current state of the art for correlated or post-Hartree–Fock calculations.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] The *aug-* prefix is added if diffuse functions are included in the basis.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] For period-3 atoms (Al–Ar), additional functions have turned out to be necessary; these are the cc-pV(N+d)Z basis sets.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Even larger atoms may employ pseudopotential basis sets, cc-pVNZ-PP, or relativistic-contracted Douglas-Kroll basis sets, cc-pVNZ-DK.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] While the usual Dunning basis sets are for valence-only calculations, the sets can be augmented with further functions that describe core electron correlation.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] These core-valence sets (cc-pCVXZ) can be used to approach the exact solution to the all-electron problem, and they are necessary for accurate geometric and nuclear property calculations.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Weighted core-valence sets (cc-pwCVXZ) have also been recently suggested.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] The weighted sets aim to capture core-valence correlation, while neglecting most of core-core correlation, in order to yield accurate geometries with smaller cost than the cc-pCVXZ sets.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Diffuse functions can also be added for describing anions and long-range interactions such as Van der Waals forces, or to perform electronic excited-state calculations, electric field property calculations.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] A recipe for constructing additional augmented functions exists; as many as five augmented functions have been used in second hyperpolarizability calculations in the literature.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Because of the rigorous construction of these basis sets, extrapolation can be done for almost any energetic property.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] However, care must be taken when extrapolating energy differences as the individual energy components converge at different rates: the Hartree–Fock energy converges exponentially, whereas the correlation energy converges only polynomially.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] To understand how to get the number of functions, consider the cc-pVDZ basis set for H: There are two *s* (*L* = 0) orbitals and one *p* (*L* = 1) orbital that has 3 angular-momentum components along the *z*-axis (*m*L = −1,0,1) corresponding to *p**x*, *p**y* and *p**z*.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Thus, there are five spatial orbitals in total.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Note that each orbital can hold two electrons of opposite spin.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] As another example, Ar [1s, 2s, 2p, 3s, 3p] has 3 s orbitals (*L* = 0) and 2 sets of p orbitals (*L* = 1).
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Using cc-pVDZ, orbitals are [1s, 2s, 2p, 3s, 3s, 3p, 3p, 3d'] (where ' represents the added in polarisation orbitals), with 4 s orbitals (4 basis functions), 3 sets of p orbitals (3 × 3 = 9 basis functions), and 1 set of d orbitals (5 basis functions).
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Adding up the basis functions gives a total of 18 functions for Ar with the cc-pVDZ basis-set.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Density-functional theory has recently become widely used in computational chemistry.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] However, the correlation-consistent basis sets described above are suboptimal for density-functional theory, because the correlation-consistent sets have been designed for post-Hartree–Fock, while density-functional theory exhibits much more rapid basis set convergence than wave function methods.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Adopting a similar methodology to the correlation-consistent series, Frank Jensen introduced polarization-consistent (pc-n) basis sets as a way to quickly converge density functional theory calculations to the complete basis set limit.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Like the Dunning sets, the pc-n sets can be combined with basis set extrapolation techniques to obtain CBS values.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] The pc-n sets can be augmented with diffuse functions to obtain augpc-n sets.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Some of the various valence adaptations of Karlsruhe basis sets are briefly described below.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Gaussian-type orbital basis sets are typically optimized to reproduce the lowest possible energy for the systems used to train the basis set.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] However, the convergence of the energy does not imply convergence of other properties, such as nuclear magnetic shieldings, the dipole moment, or the electron momentum density, which probe different aspects of the electronic wave function.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Manninen and Vaara have proposed completeness-optimized basis sets, where the exponents are obtained by maximization of the one-electron completeness profile instead of minimization of the energy.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Completeness-optimized basis sets are a way to easily approach the complete basis set limit of any property at any level of theory, and the procedure is simple to automatize.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Completeness-optimized basis sets are tailored to a specific property.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] This way, the flexibility of the basis set can be focused on the computational demands of the chosen property, typically yielding much faster convergence to the complete basis set limit than is achievable with energy-optimized basis sets.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Here, only the two parameters $\alpha _{l}$ and $\beta _{l}$ must be optimized, significantly reducing the dimension of the search space or even avoiding the exponent optimization problem.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] In order to properly describe electronic delocalized states, a previously optimized standard basis set can be complemented with additional delocalized Gaussian functions with small exponent values, generated by the even-tempered scheme.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] This approach has also been employed to generate basis sets for other types of quantum particles rather than electrons, like quantum nuclei, negative muons or positrons.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] In addition to localized basis sets, plane-wave basis sets can also be used in quantum-chemical simulations.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Typically, the choice of the plane wave basis set is based on a cutoff energy.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] The plane waves in the simulation cell that fit below the energy criterion are then included in the calculation.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] These basis sets are popular in calculations involving three-dimensional periodic boundary conditions.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] The main advantage of a plane-wave basis is that it is guaranteed to converge in a *smooth, monotonic manner* to the target wavefunction.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] In contrast, when localized basis sets are used, monotonic convergence to the basis set limit may be difficult due to problems with over-completeness: in a large basis set, functions on different atoms start to look alike, and many eigenvalues of the overlap matrix approach zero.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] In addition, certain integrals and operations are much easier to program and carry out with plane-wave basis functions than with their localized counterparts.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] For example, the kinetic energy operator is diagonal in the reciprocal space.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Integrals over real-space operators can be efficiently carried out using fast Fourier transforms.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] The properties of the Fourier Transform allow a vector representing the gradient of the total energy with respect to the plane-wave coefficients to be calculated with a computational effort that scales as NPW*ln(NPW) where NPW is the number of plane-waves.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] When this property is combined with separable pseudopotentials of the Kleinman-Bylander type and pre-conditioned conjugate gradient solution techniques, the dynamic simulation of periodic problems containing hundreds of atoms becomes possible.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] In practice, plane-wave basis sets are often used in combination with an 'effective core potential' or pseudopotential, so that the plane waves are only used to describe the valence charge density.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] This is because core electrons tend to be concentrated very close to the atomic nuclei, resulting in large wavefunction and density gradients near the nuclei which are not easily described by a plane-wave basis set unless a very high energy cutoff, and therefore small wavelength, is used.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] This combined method of a plane-wave basis set with a core pseudopotential is often abbreviated as a *PSPW* calculation.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Furthermore, as all functions in the basis are mutually orthogonal and are not associated with any particular atom, plane-wave basis sets do not exhibit basis-set superposition error.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] However, the plane-wave basis set is dependent on the size of the simulation cell, complicating cell size optimization.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Due to the assumption of periodic boundary conditions, plane-wave basis sets are less well suited to gas-phase calculations than localized basis sets.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Large regions of vacuum need to be added on all sides of the gas-phase molecule in order to avoid interactions with the molecule and its periodic copies.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] However, the plane waves use a similar accuracy to describe the vacuum region as the region where the molecule is, meaning that obtaining the truly noninteracting limit may be computationally costly.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] A combination of some of the properties of localized basis sets and plane-wave approaches is achieved by linearized augmented-plane-wave (LAPW) basis sets.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] These are based on a partitioning of space into nonoverlapping spheres around each atom and an interstitial region in between the spheres.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] An LAPW basis function is a plane wave in the interstitial region, which is augmented by numerical atomic functions in each sphere.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] The numerical atomic functions hereby provide a linearized representation of wave functions for arbitrary energies around automatically determined energy parameters.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Similarly to plane-wave basis sets an LAPW basis set is mainly determined by a cutoff parameter for the plane-wave representation in the interstitial region.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] In the spheres the variational degrees of freedom can be extended by adding local orbitals to the basis set.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] This allows representations of wavefunctions beyond the linearized description.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] The plane waves in the interstitial region imply three-dimensional periodic boundary conditions, though it is possible to introduce additional augmentation regions to reduce this to one or two dimensions, e.g., for the description of chain-like structures or thin films.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] The atomic-like representation in the spheres allows to treat each atom with its potential singularity at the nucleus and to not rely on a pseudopotential approximation.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] The disadvantage of LAPW basis sets is its complex definition, which comes with many parameters that have to be controlled either by the user or an automatic recipe.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Another consequence of the form of the basis set are complex mathematical expressions, e.g., for the calculation of a Hamiltonian matrix or atomic forces.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Real-space approaches offer powerful methods to solve electronic structure problems thanks to their controllable accuracy.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Real-space basis sets can be thought to arise from the theory of interpolation, as the central idea is to represent the (unknown) orbitals in terms of some set of interpolation functions.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Various methods have been proposed for constructing the solution in real space, including finite elements, basis splines, Lagrange sinc-functions, and wavelets.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Finite difference algorithms are also often included in this category, even though precisely speaking, they do not form a proper basis set and are not variational unlike e.g. finite element methods.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] A common feature of all real-space methods is that the accuracy of the numerical basis set is improvable, so that the complete basis set limit can be reached in a systematical manner.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] For example, in finite element methods (FEMs), the wave function is represented as a linear combination of a set of piecewise polynomials.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] Lagrange interpolating polynomials (LIPs) are a commonly used basis for FEM calculations.
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] The local interpolation error in LIP basis of order n is of the form $h^{n+1}\max f^{(n+1)}(\xi )$ .
[src:hartree-fock/basis-set-chemistry] The use of high-order LIPs has been shown to be highly beneficial for accuracy.
[src:hartree-fock/fock-matrix] The Fock matrix is defined by the Fock operator.
[src:hartree-fock/fock-matrix] where ${\hat {J}}_{j}$ and ${\hat {K}}_{j}$ are the Coulomb and exchange operators, and *i* runs over the total *N* spin orbitals.
[src:hartree-fock/fock-matrix] In the closed-shell case, it can be simplified by considering only the spatial orbitals by noting that the ${\hat {J}}$ terms are duplicated and the exchange terms are null between different spins.
[src:hartree-fock/fock-matrix] , defining the quantum effect produced by exchanging two electrons.
[src:hartree-fock/fock-matrix] The Coulomb operator is multiplied by two since there are two electrons in each occupied orbital.
[src:hartree-fock/fock-matrix] The exchange operator is not multiplied by two since it has a non-zero result only for electrons which have the same spin as the *i*-th electron.
[src:hartree-fock/fock-matrix] For systems with unpaired electrons there are many choices of Fock matrices.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] In computational physics and chemistry, the **Hartree–Fock (HF) method** is used for approximating the wave function and the energy of a quantum many-body system in a stationary state.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] It is named after Douglas Hartree and Vladimir Fock.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] The Hartree–Fock method often assumes that the exact N -body wave function of the system can be approximated by a single Slater determinant (in the case where the particles are fermions) or by a single permanent (in the case of bosons) of N spin-orbitals.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] By invoking the variational method, one can derive a set of N coupled equations for the N spin orbitals.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] A solution of these equations yields the Hartree–Fock wave function and energy of the system.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Hartree–Fock approximation is an instance of mean-field theory, where neglecting higher-order fluctuations in order parameter allows interaction terms to be replaced with quadratic terms, obtaining exactly solvable Hamiltonians.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Especially in the older literature, the Hartree–Fock method is also called the **self-consistent field method** (**SCF**).
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] In deriving what is now called the Hartree equation as an approximate solution of the Schrödinger equation, Hartree required the final field as computed from the charge distribution to be "self-consistent" with the assumed initial field.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Thus, self-consistency was a requirement of the solution.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] The solutions to the non-linear Hartree–Fock equations also behave as if each particle is subjected to the mean field created by all other particles (see the Fock operator below), and hence the terminology continued.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] The equations are almost universally solved by means of an iterative method, although the fixed-point iteration algorithm does not always converge.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] This solution scheme is not the only one possible and is not an essential feature of the Hartree–Fock method.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] The Hartree–Fock method finds its typical application in the solution of the Schrödinger equation for atoms, molecules, nanostructures and solids but it has also found widespread use in nuclear physics.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] (See Hartree–Fock–Bogoliubov method for a discussion of its application in nuclear structure theory).
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] For both atoms and molecules, the Hartree–Fock solution is the central starting point for most methods that describe the many-electron system more accurately.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] The rest of this article will focus on applications in electronic structure theory suitable for molecules with the atom as a special case.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] The discussion here is only for the restricted Hartree–Fock method, where the atom or molecule is a closed-shell system with all orbitals (atomic or molecular) doubly occupied.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Open-shell systems, where some of the electrons are not paired, can be dealt with by either the restricted open-shell or the unrestricted Hartree–Fock methods.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] The origin of the Hartree–Fock method dates back to the end of the 1920s, soon after the discovery of the Schrödinger equation in 1926.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Douglas Hartree's methods were guided by some earlier, semi-empirical methods of the early 1920s (by E.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Lindsay, and himself) set in the old quantum theory of Bohr.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] In the Bohr model of the atom, the energy of a state with principal quantum number *n* is given in atomic units as $E=-1/n^{2}$ .
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] It was observed from atomic spectra that the energy levels of many-electron atoms are well described by applying a modified version of Bohr's formula.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] The existence of a non-zero quantum defect was attributed to electron–electron repulsion, which clearly does not exist in the isolated hydrogen atom.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] This repulsion resulted in partial screening of the bare nuclear charge.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] These early researchers later introduced other potentials containing additional empirical parameters with the hope of better reproducing the experimental data.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Hartree introduced a procedure, which he called the self-consistent field method, to calculate approximate wave functions and energies for atoms and ions.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Hartree sought to do away with empirical parameters and solve the many-body time-independent Schrödinger equation from fundamental physical principles, i.e., ab initio.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] His first proposed method of solution became known as the *Hartree method*, or *Hartree product*.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] However, many of Hartree's contemporaries did not understand the physical reasoning behind the Hartree method: it appeared to many people to contain empirical elements, and its connection to the solution of the many-body Schrödinger equation was unclear.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Gaunt independently showed that the Hartree method could be couched on a sounder theoretical basis by applying the variational principle to an ansatz (trial wave function) as a product of single-particle functions.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Fock independently pointed out that the Hartree method did not respect the principle of antisymmetry of the wave function.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] The Hartree method used the Pauli exclusion principle in its older formulation, forbidding the presence of two electrons in the same quantum state.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] However, this was shown to be fundamentally incomplete in its neglect of quantum statistics.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] The original Hartree method can then be viewed as an approximation to the Hartree–Fock method by neglecting exchange.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Fock's original method relied heavily on group theory and was too abstract for contemporary physicists to understand and implement.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] In 1935, Hartree reformulated the method to be more suitable for the purposes of calculation.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] The Hartree–Fock method, despite its physically more accurate picture, was little used until the advent of electronic computers in the 1950s due to the much greater computational demands over the early Hartree method and empirical models.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Initially, both the Hartree method and the Hartree–Fock method were applied exclusively to atoms, where the spherical symmetry of the system allowed one to greatly simplify the problem.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] These approximate methods were (and are) often used together with the central field approximation to impose the condition that electrons in the same shell have the same radial part and to restrict the variational solution to be a spin eigenfunction.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Even so, calculating a solution by hand using the Hartree–Fock equations for a medium-sized atom was laborious; small molecules required computational resources far beyond what was available before 1950.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] The Hartree–Fock method is typically used to solve the time-independent Schrödinger equation for a multi-electron atom or molecule as described in the Born–Oppenheimer approximation.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Since there are no known analytic solutions for many-electron systems (there *are* solutions for one-electron systems such as hydrogenic atoms and the diatomic hydrogen cation), the problem is solved numerically.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Relaxation of the last two approximations give rise to many so-called post-Hartree–Fock methods.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] The variational theorem states that for a time-independent Hamiltonian operator, any trial wave function will have an energy expectation value that is greater than or equal to the true ground-state wave function corresponding to the given Hamiltonian.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Because of this, the Hartree–Fock energy is an upper bound to the true ground-state energy of a given molecule.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] In the context of the Hartree–Fock method, the best possible solution is at the *Hartree–Fock limit*; i.e., the limit of the Hartree–Fock energy as the basis set approaches completeness.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] (The other is the *full-CI limit*, where the last two approximations of the Hartree–Fock theory as described above are completely undone.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] It is only when both limits are attained that the exact solution, up to the Born–Oppenheimer approximation, is obtained.) The Hartree–Fock energy is the minimal energy for a single Slater determinant.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] The starting point for the Hartree–Fock method is a set of approximate one-electron wave functions known as *spin-orbitals*.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] For an atomic orbital calculation, these are typically the orbitals for a hydrogen-like atom (an atom with only one electron, but the appropriate nuclear charge).
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] For a molecular orbital or crystalline calculation, the initial approximate one-electron wave functions are typically a linear combination of atomic orbitals (LCAO).
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] The orbitals above only account for the presence of other electrons in an average manner.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] In the Hartree–Fock method, the effect of other electrons are accounted for in a mean-field theory context.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] The orbitals are optimized by requiring them to minimize the energy of the respective Slater determinant.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] The resultant variational conditions on the orbitals lead to a new one-electron operator, the Fock operator.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] At the minimum, the occupied orbitals are eigensolutions to the Fock operator via a unitary transformation between themselves.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] The Fock operator is an effective one-electron Hamiltonian operator being the sum of two terms.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] The first is a sum of kinetic-energy operators for each electron, the internuclear repulsion energy, and a sum of nuclear–electronic Coulombic attraction terms.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] The second are Coulombic repulsion terms between electrons in a mean-field theory description; a net repulsion energy for each electron in the system, which is calculated by treating all of the other electrons within the molecule as a smooth distribution of negative charge.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] This is the major simplification inherent in the Hartree–Fock method and is equivalent to the fifth simplification in the above list.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Since the Fock operator depends on the orbitals used to construct the corresponding Fock matrix, the eigenfunctions of the Fock operator are in turn new orbitals, which can be used to construct a new Fock operator.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] In this way, the Hartree–Fock orbitals are optimized iteratively until the change in total electronic energy falls below a predefined threshold.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] In this way, a set of self-consistent one-electron orbitals is calculated.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] The Hartree–Fock electronic wave function is then the Slater determinant constructed from these orbitals.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Following the basic postulates of quantum mechanics, the Hartree–Fock wave function can then be used to compute any desired chemical or physical property within the framework of the Hartree–Fock method and the approximations employed.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] To derive the Hartree-Fock equation we minimize the energy functional for N electrons with orthonormal constraints.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] We choose a basis set $\phi _{i}(x_{i})$ in which the Lagrange multiplier matrix $\lambda _{ij}$ becomes diagonal, i.e. $\lambda _{ij}=\epsilon _{i}\delta _{ij}$ .
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] The factor 1/2 before the double integrals in the molecular Hamiltonian drops out due to symmetry and the product rule.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] The exchange operator has no classical analogue and can only be defined as an integral operator.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] The solution $\phi _{k}$ and $\epsilon _{k}$ are called molecular orbital and orbital energy respectively.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Although Hartree-Fock equation appears in the form of a eigenvalue problem, the Fock operator itself depends on $\phi$ and must be solved by a different technique.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] The general optimal total energy $E_{HF}$ can be written in terms of spin orbitals.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] where i and j index spin orbitals, ${\hat {J}}_{ij}$ and ${\hat {K}}_{ij}$ are matrix elements of the Coulomb and exchange operators respectively, and $V_{\text{nucl}}$ is the total electrostatic repulsion between all the nuclei in the molecule.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] The total energy is not simply equal to the sum of orbital energies.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] where i and j now index spatial orbitals.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Typically, in modern Hartree–Fock calculations, the one-electron wave functions are approximated by a linear combination of atomic orbitals.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] These atomic orbitals are called Slater-type orbitals.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Furthermore, it is very common for the "atomic orbitals" in use to actually be composed of a linear combination of one or more Gaussian-type orbitals, rather than Slater-type orbitals, in the interests of saving large amounts of computation time.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Various basis sets are used in practice, most of which are composed of Gaussian functions.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] In some applications, an orthogonalization method such as the Gram–Schmidt process is performed in order to produce a set of orthogonal basis functions.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] This can in principle save computational time when the computer is solving the Roothaan–Hall equations by converting the overlap matrix effectively to an identity matrix.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Numerical stability can be a problem with this procedure and there are various ways of combatting this instability.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] One of the most basic and generally applicable is called *F-mixing* or damping.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] With F-mixing, once a single-electron wave function is calculated, it is not used directly.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Instead, some combination of that calculated wave function and the previous wave functions for that electron is used, the most common being a simple linear combination of the calculated and immediately preceding wave function.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] A clever dodge, employed by Hartree, for atomic calculations was to increase the nuclear charge, thus pulling all the electrons closer together.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] As the system stabilised, this was gradually reduced to the correct charge.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] In molecular calculations a similar approach is sometimes used by first calculating the wave function for a positive ion and then to use these orbitals as the starting point for the neutral molecule.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Modern molecular Hartree–Fock computer programs use a variety of methods to ensure convergence of the Roothaan–Hall equations.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Of the five simplifications outlined in the section "Hartree–Fock algorithm", the fifth is typically the most important.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Neglect of electron correlation can lead to large deviations from experimental results.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] A number of approaches to this weakness, collectively called post-Hartree–Fock methods, have been devised to include electron correlation to the multi-electron wave function.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] One of these approaches, Møller–Plesset perturbation theory, treats correlation as a perturbation of the Fock operator.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Others expand the true multi-electron wave function in terms of a linear combination of Slater determinants—such as multi-configurational self-consistent field, configuration interaction, quadratic configuration interaction, and complete active space SCF (CASSCF).
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Still others (such as variational quantum Monte Carlo) modify the Hartree–Fock wave function by multiplying it by a correlation function ("Jastrow" factor), a term which is explicitly a function of multiple electrons that cannot be decomposed into independent single-particle functions.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] An alternative to Hartree–Fock calculations used in some cases is density functional theory, which treats both exchange and correlation energies, albeit approximately.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Indeed, it is common to use calculations that are a hybrid of the two methods—the popular B3LYP scheme is one such hybrid functional method.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] Another option is to use modern valence bond methods.
[src:hartree-fock/hartree-fock-method] For a list of software packages known to handle Hartree–Fock calculations, particularly for molecules and solids, see the list of quantum chemistry and solid state physics software.
[src:hartree-fock/roothaan-equations] The **Roothaan equations** are a representation of the Hartree–Fock equation in a non orthonormal basis set which can be of Gaussian-type or Slater-type.
[src:hartree-fock/roothaan-equations] It applies to closed-shell molecules or atoms where all molecular orbitals or atomic orbitals, respectively, are doubly occupied.
[src:hartree-fock/roothaan-equations] This is generally called restricted Hartree–Fock theory.
[src:hartree-fock/roothaan-equations] The method was developed independently by Clemens C.
[src:hartree-fock/roothaan-equations] Hall in 1951, and is thus sometimes called the *Roothaan-Hall equations*.
[src:hartree-fock/roothaan-equations] where F is the Fock matrix (which depends on the coefficients C due to electron-electron interactions), C is a matrix of coefficients, S is the overlap matrix of the basis functions, and $\epsilon$ is the (diagonal, by convention) matrix of orbital energies.
[src:hartree-fock/roothaan-equations] In the case of an orthonormalised basis set the overlap matrix, S, reduces to the identity matrix.
[src:hartree-fock/roothaan-equations] These equations are essentially a special case of a Galerkin method applied to the Hartree–Fock equation using a particular basis set.
[src:hartree-fock/roothaan-equations] In contrast to the Hartree–Fock equations - which are integro-differential equations - the Roothaan–Hall equations have a matrix-form.
[src:hartree-fock/roothaan-equations] Therefore, they can be solved using standard techniques.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] In quantum mechanics, a **Slater determinant** is an expression that describes the wave function of a multi-fermionic system.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] It satisfies anti-symmetry requirements, and consequently the Pauli principle, by changing sign upon exchange of two fermions.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] Only a small subset of all possible many-body fermionic wave functions can be written as a single Slater determinant, but those form an important and useful subset because of their simplicity.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] The Slater determinant arises from the consideration of a wave function for a collection of electrons, each with a wave function known as the spin-orbital $\chi (\mathbf {x} )$ , where $\mathbf {x}$ denotes the position and spin of a single electron.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] A Slater determinant containing two electrons with the same spin orbital would correspond to a wave function that is zero everywhere.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] The Slater determinant is named for John C.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] Slater, who introduced the determinant in 1929 as a means of ensuring the antisymmetry of a many-electron wave function, although the wave function in the determinant form first appeared independently in Heisenberg's and Dirac's articles three years earlier.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] The simplest way to approximate the wave function of a many-particle system is to take the product of properly chosen orthogonal wave functions of the individual particles.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] This expression is used in the Hartree method as an ansatz for the many-particle wave function and is known as a Hartree product.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] However, it is not satisfactory for fermions because the wave function above is not antisymmetric under exchange of any two of the fermions, as it must be according to the Pauli exclusion principle.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] This does not hold for the Hartree product, which therefore does not satisfy the Pauli principle.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] where the coefficient is the normalization factor.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] This wave function is now antisymmetric and no longer distinguishes between fermions (that is, one cannot indicate an ordinal number to a specific particle, and the indices given are interchangeable).
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] Moreover, it also goes to zero if any two spin orbitals of two fermions are the same.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] This is equivalent to satisfying the Pauli exclusion principle.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] The expression can be generalised to any number of fermions by writing it as a determinant.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] where the last two expressions use a shorthand for Slater determinants: The normalization constant is implied by noting the number N, and only the one-particle wavefunctions (first shorthand) or the indices for the fermion coordinates (second shorthand) are written down.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] All skipped labels are implied to behave in ascending sequence.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] The linear combination of Hartree products for the two-particle case is identical with the Slater determinant for *N* = 2.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] The use of Slater determinants ensures an antisymmetrized function at the outset.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] In the same way, the use of Slater determinants ensures conformity to the Pauli principle.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] Indeed, the Slater determinant vanishes if the set $\{\chi _{i}\}$ is linearly dependent.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] In particular, this is the case when two (or more) spin orbitals are the same.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] In chemistry one expresses this fact by stating that no two electrons with the same spin can occupy the same spatial orbital.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] Many properties of the Slater determinant come to life with an example in a non-relativistic many electron problem.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] and where we will distinguish in the Hamiltonian between the first set of terms as ${\hat {G}}_{1}$ (the "1" particle terms) and the last term ${\hat {G}}_{2}$ (the "2" particle term) which contains exchange term for a Slater determinant.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] The two parts will behave differently when they have to interact with a Slater determinant wave function.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] In the above expression, we can just select the identical permutation in the determinant in the left part, since all the other N! − 1 permutations would give the same result as the selected one.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] This result shows that the anti-symmetrization of the product does not have any effect for the one particle terms and it behaves as it would do in the case of the simple Hartree product.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] Which tells us that to the extent of the one-particle terms the wave functions of the electrons are independent of each other and the expectation value of total system is given by the sum of expectation value of the single particles.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] The first contribution is called the "coulomb" term or "coulomb" integral and the second is the "exchange" term or exchange integral.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] Sometimes different range of index in the summation is used ${\textstyle \sum _{ij}}$ since the Coulomb and exchange contributions exactly cancel each other for $i=j$ .
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] It is important to notice explicitly that the exchange term, which is always positive for local spin-orbitals, is absent in the simple Hartree product.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] Hence the electron-electron repulsive energy $\langle \Psi _{0}|G_{2}|\Psi _{0}\rangle$ on the antisymmetrized product of spin-orbitals is always lower than the electron-electron repulsive energy on the simple Hartree product of the same spin-orbitals.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] Since exchange bielectronic integrals are different from zero only for spin-orbitals with parallel spins, we link the decrease in energy with the physical fact that electrons with parallel spin are kept apart in real space in Slater determinant states.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] The space of all pure quantum states in a Hilbert space ${\mathcal {H}}$ can be identified with a projective Hilbert space, the manifold of all 1-dimensional subspaces of ${\mathcal {H}}$ , since states differing by a global phase represent the same physical state.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] A Slater determinant in the tensor product ${\mathcal {H}}^{\otimes N}$ is uniquely determined, up to a global phase, by the N -dimensional subspace of ${\mathcal {H}}$ spanned by the corresponding one-particle states.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] The space of states that can be written as a single Slater determinant in ${\mathcal {H}}$ forms a smooth manifold and projective algebraic variety which is naturally identified with the Grassmannian $\mathbf {Gr} _{N}({\mathcal {H}})$ .
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] Its embedding into the projective many-particle Hilbert space $\mathbf {P} ({\mathcal {H}}^{\otimes N})$ is equivalent to the Plücker embedding, which corresponds exactly to taking the many-particle Slater determinant of a given set of N one-particle states.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] In quantum chemistry, the geometric structure of these spaces plays an important role in theoretical analysis of the Hartree-Fock method and can be used to prove theoretical results on the existence of solutions to the Hartree-Fock equations.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] Most fermionic wavefunctions cannot be represented as a Slater determinant.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] The best Slater approximation to a given fermionic wave function can be defined to be the one that maximizes the overlap between the Slater determinant and the target wave function.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] The maximal overlap is a geometric measure of entanglement between the fermions.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] A single Slater determinant is used as an approximation to the electronic wavefunction in Hartree–Fock theory.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] In more accurate theories (such as configuration interaction and MCSCF), a linear combination of Slater determinants is needed.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] Boys to refer to a Slater determinant of orthonormal orbitals, but this term is rarely used.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] Unlike fermions that are subject to the Pauli exclusion principle, two or more bosons can occupy the same single-particle quantum state.
[src:hartree-fock/slater-determinant] Wavefunctions describing systems of identical bosons are symmetric under the exchange of particles and can be expanded in terms of permanents.
